3682 ////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
3683 /// Draw expression varexp for specified entries.
3684 ///
3685 /// \return -1 in case of error or number of selected events in case of success.
3686 ///
3687 /// This function accepts TCut objects as arguments.
3688 /// Useful to use the string operator +
3689 ///
3690 /// Example:
3691 ///
3692 /// ~~~ {.cpp}
3693 /// ntuple.Draw("x",cut1+cut2+cut3);
3694 /// ~~~
3695 
3696 
3697 Long64_t TTree::Draw(const char* varexp, const TCut& selection, Option_t* option, Long64_t nentries, Long64_t firstentry)
3698 {
3699  return TTree::Draw(varexp, selection.GetTitle(), option, nentries, firstentry);
3700 }
3701 
3702 ////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
3703 /// Draw expression varexp for specified entries.
3704 ///
3705 /// \return -1 in case of error or number of selected events in case of success.
3706 ///
3707 /// \param [in] varexp is an expression of the general form
3708 /// - "e1" produces a 1-d histogram (TH1F) of expression "e1"
3709 /// - "e1:e2" produces an unbinned 2-d scatter-plot (TGraph) of "e1"
3710 /// on the y-axis versus "e2" on the x-axis
3711 /// - "e1:e2:e3" produces an unbinned 3-d scatter-plot (TPolyMarker3D) of "e1"
3712 /// vs "e2" vs "e3" on the x-, y-, z-axis, respectively.
3713 /// - "e1:e2:e3:e4" produces an unbinned 3-d scatter-plot (TPolyMarker3D) of "e1"
3714 /// vs "e2" vs "e3" and "e4" mapped on the current color palette.
3715 /// (to create histograms in the 2, 3, and 4 dimensional case,
3716 /// see section "Saving the result of Draw to an histogram")
3717 ///
3718 /// Example:
3719 /// - varexp = x simplest case: draw a 1-Dim distribution of column named x
3720 /// - varexp = sqrt(x) : draw distribution of sqrt(x)
3721 /// - varexp = x*y/z
3722 /// - varexp = y:sqrt(x) 2-Dim distribution of y versus sqrt(x)
3723 /// - varexp = px:py:pz:2.5*E produces a 3-d scatter-plot of px vs py ps pz
3724 /// and the color number of each marker will be 2.5*E.
3725 /// If the color number is negative it is set to 0.
3726 /// If the color number is greater than the current number of colors
3727 /// it is set to the highest color number.The default number of
3728 /// colors is 50. see TStyle::SetPalette for setting a new color palette.
3729 ///
3730 /// Note that the variables e1, e2 or e3 may contain a selection.
3731 /// example, if e1= x*(y<0), the value histogrammed will be x if y<0
3732 /// and will be 0 otherwise.
3733 ///
3734 /// The expressions can use all the operations and build-in functions
3735 /// supported by TFormula (See TFormula::Analyze), including free
3736 /// standing function taking numerical arguments (TMath::Bessel).
3737 /// In addition, you can call member functions taking numerical
3738 /// arguments. For example:
3739 /// ~~~ {.cpp}
3740 /// TMath::BreitWigner(fPx,3,2)
3741 /// event.GetHistogram().GetXaxis().GetXmax()
3742 /// ~~~
3743 /// Note: You can only pass expression that depend on the TTree's data
3744 /// to static functions and you can only call non-static member function
3745 /// with 'fixed' parameters.
3746 ///
3747 /// \param [in] selection is an expression with a combination of the columns.
3748 /// In a selection all the C++ operators are authorized.
3749 /// The value corresponding to the selection expression is used as a weight
3750 /// to fill the histogram.
3751 /// If the expression includes only boolean operations, the result
3752 /// is 0 or 1. If the result is 0, the histogram is not filled.
3753 /// In general, the expression may be of the form:
3754 /// ~~~ {.cpp}
3755 /// value*(boolean expression)
3756 /// ~~~
3757 /// if boolean expression is true, the histogram is filled with
3758 /// a `weight = value`.
3759 /// Examples:
3760 /// - selection1 = "x<y && sqrt(z)>3.2"
3761 /// - selection2 = "(x+y)*(sqrt(z)>3.2)"
3762 /// - selection1 returns a weight = 0 or 1
3763 /// - selection2 returns a weight = x+y if sqrt(z)>3.2
3764 /// returns a weight = 0 otherwise.
3765 ///
3766 /// \param [in] option is the drawing option.
3767 /// - When an histogram is produced it can be any histogram drawing option
3768 /// listed in THistPainter.
3769 /// - when no option is specified:
3770 /// - the default histogram drawing option is used
3771 /// if the expression is of the form "e1".
3772 /// - if the expression is of the form "e1:e2"or "e1:e2:e3" a cloud of
3773 /// unbinned 2D or 3D points is drawn respectively.
3774 /// - if the expression has four fields "e1:e2:e3:e4" a 2D scatter is
3775 /// produced with e1 vs e2 vs e3, and e4 is mapped on the current color
3776 /// palette.
3777 /// - If option COL is specified when varexp has three fields:
3778 /// ~~~ {.cpp}
3779 /// tree.Draw("e1:e2:e3","","col");
3780 /// ~~~
3781 /// a 2D scatter is produced with e1 vs e2, and e3 is mapped on the current
3782 /// color palette. The colors for e3 are evaluated once in linear scale before
3783 /// painting. Therefore changing the pad to log scale along Z as no effect
3784 /// on the colors.
3785 /// - if expression has more than four fields the option "PARA"or "CANDLE"
3786 /// can be used.
3787 /// - If option contains the string "goff", no graphics is generated.
3788 ///
3789 /// \param [in] nentries is the number of entries to process (default is all)
3790 ///
3791 /// \param [in] firstentry is the first entry to process (default is 0)
3792 ///
3793 /// ### Drawing expressions using arrays and array elements
3794 ///
3795 /// Let assumes, a leaf fMatrix, on the branch fEvent, which is a 3 by 3 array,
3796 /// or a TClonesArray.
3797 /// In a TTree::Draw expression you can now access fMatrix using the following
3798 /// syntaxes:
3799 ///
3800 /// | String passed | What is used for each entry of the tree
3801 /// |-----------------|--------------------------------------------------------|
3802 /// | `fMatrix` | the 9 elements of fMatrix |
3803 /// | `fMatrix[][]` | the 9 elements of fMatrix |
3804 /// | `fMatrix[2][2]` | only the elements fMatrix[2][2] |
3805 /// | `fMatrix[1]` | the 3 elements fMatrix[1][0], fMatrix[1][1] and fMatrix[1][2] |
3806 /// | `fMatrix[1][]` | the 3 elements fMatrix[1][0], fMatrix[1][1] and fMatrix[1][2] |
3807 /// | `fMatrix[][0]` | the 3 elements fMatrix[0][0], fMatrix[1][0] and fMatrix[2][0] |
3808 ///
3809 /// "fEvent.fMatrix...." same as "fMatrix..." (unless there is more than one leaf named fMatrix!).
3810 ///
3811 /// In summary, if a specific index is not specified for a dimension, TTree::Draw
3812 /// will loop through all the indices along this dimension. Leaving off the
3813 /// last (right most) dimension of specifying then with the two characters '[]'
3814 /// is equivalent. For variable size arrays (and TClonesArray) the range
3815 /// of the first dimension is recalculated for each entry of the tree.
3816 /// You can also specify the index as an expression of any other variables from the
3817 /// tree.
3818 ///
3819 /// TTree::Draw also now properly handling operations involving 2 or more arrays.
3820 ///
3821 /// Let assume a second matrix fResults[5][2], here are a sample of some
3822 /// of the possible combinations, the number of elements they produce and
3823 /// the loop used:
3824 ///
3825 /// | expression | element(s) | Loop |
3826 /// |----------------------------------|------------|--------------------------|
3827 /// | `fMatrix[2][1] - fResults[5][2]` | one | no loop |
3828 /// | `fMatrix[2][] - fResults[5][2]` | three | on 2nd dim fMatrix |
3829 /// | `fMatrix[2][] - fResults[5][]` | two | on both 2nd dimensions |
3830 /// | `fMatrix[][2] - fResults[][1]` | three | on both 1st dimensions |
3831 /// | `fMatrix[][2] - fResults[][]` | six | on both 1st and 2nd dimensions of fResults |
3832 /// | `fMatrix[][2] - fResults[3][]` | two | on 1st dim of fMatrix and 2nd of fResults (at the same time) |
3833 /// | `fMatrix[][] - fResults[][]` | six | on 1st dim then on 2nd dim |
3834 /// | `fMatrix[][fResult[][]]` | 30 | on 1st dim of fMatrix then on both dimensions of fResults. The value if fResults[j][k] is used as the second index of fMatrix.|
3835 ///
3836 ///
3837 /// In summary, TTree::Draw loops through all unspecified dimensions. To
3838 /// figure out the range of each loop, we match each unspecified dimension
3839 /// from left to right (ignoring ALL dimensions for which an index has been
3840 /// specified), in the equivalent loop matched dimensions use the same index
3841 /// and are restricted to the smallest range (of only the matched dimensions).
3842 /// When involving variable arrays, the range can of course be different
3843 /// for each entry of the tree.
3844 ///
3845 /// So the loop equivalent to "fMatrix[][2] - fResults[3][]" is:
3846 /// ~~~ {.cpp}
3847 /// for (Int_t i0; i < min(3,2); i++) {
3848 /// use the value of (fMatrix[i0][2] - fMatrix[3][i0])
3849 /// }
3850 /// ~~~
3851 /// So the loop equivalent to "fMatrix[][2] - fResults[][]" is:
3852 /// ~~~ {.cpp}
3853 /// for (Int_t i0; i < min(3,5); i++) {
3854 /// for (Int_t i1; i1 < 2; i1++) {
3855 /// use the value of (fMatrix[i0][2] - fMatrix[i0][i1])
3856 /// }
3857 /// }
3858 /// ~~~
3859 /// So the loop equivalent to "fMatrix[][] - fResults[][]" is:
3860 /// ~~~ {.cpp}
3861 /// for (Int_t i0; i < min(3,5); i++) {
3862 /// for (Int_t i1; i1 < min(3,2); i1++) {
3863 /// use the value of (fMatrix[i0][i1] - fMatrix[i0][i1])
3864 /// }
3865 /// }
3866 /// ~~~
3867 /// So the loop equivalent to "fMatrix[][fResults[][]]" is:
3868 /// ~~~ {.cpp}
3869 /// for (Int_t i0; i0 < 3; i0++) {
3870 /// for (Int_t j2; j2 < 5; j2++) {
3871 /// for (Int_t j3; j3 < 2; j3++) {
3872 /// i1 = fResults[j2][j3];
3873 /// use the value of fMatrix[i0][i1]
3874 /// }
3875 /// }
3876 /// ~~~
3877 /// ### Retrieving the result of Draw
3878 ///
3879 /// By default the temporary histogram created is called "htemp", but only in
3880 /// the one dimensional Draw("e1") it contains the TTree's data points. For
3881 /// a two dimensional Draw, the data is filled into a TGraph which is named
3882 /// "Graph". They can be retrieved by calling
3883 /// ~~~ {.cpp}
3884 /// TH1F *htemp = (TH1F*)gPad->GetPrimitive("htemp"); // 1D
3885 /// TGraph *graph = (TGraph*)gPad->GetPrimitive("Graph"); // 2D
3886 /// ~~~
3887 /// For a three and four dimensional Draw the TPolyMarker3D is unnamed, and
3888 /// cannot be retrieved.
3889 ///
3890 /// gPad always contains a TH1 derived object called "htemp" which allows to
3891 /// access the axes:
3892 /// ~~~ {.cpp}
3893 /// TGraph *graph = (TGraph*)gPad->GetPrimitive("Graph"); // 2D
3894 /// TH2F *htemp = (TH2F*)gPad->GetPrimitive("htemp"); // empty, but has axes
3895 /// TAxis *xaxis = htemp->GetXaxis();
3896 /// ~~~
3897 /// ### Saving the result of Draw to an histogram
3898 ///
3899 /// If varexp0 contains >>hnew (following the variable(s) name(s),
3900 /// the new histogram created is called hnew and it is kept in the current
3901 /// directory (and also the current pad). This works for all dimensions.
3902 ///
3903 /// Example:
3904 /// ~~~ {.cpp}
3905 /// tree.Draw("sqrt(x)>>hsqrt","y>0")
3906 /// ~~~
3907 /// will draw `sqrt(x)` and save the histogram as "hsqrt" in the current
3908 /// directory. To retrieve it do:
3909 /// ~~~ {.cpp}
3910 /// TH1F *hsqrt = (TH1F*)gDirectory->Get("hsqrt");
3911 /// ~~~
3912 /// The binning information is taken from the environment variables
3913 /// ~~~ {.cpp}
3914 /// Hist.Binning.?D.?
3915 /// ~~~
3916 /// In addition, the name of the histogram can be followed by up to 9
3917 /// numbers between '(' and ')', where the numbers describe the
3918 /// following:
3919 ///
3920 /// - 1 - bins in x-direction
3921 /// - 2 - lower limit in x-direction
3922 /// - 3 - upper limit in x-direction
3923 /// - 4-6 same for y-direction
3924 /// - 7-9 same for z-direction
3925 ///
3926 /// When a new binning is used the new value will become the default.
3927 /// Values can be skipped.
3928 ///
3929 /// Example:
3930 /// ~~~ {.cpp}
3931 /// tree.Draw("sqrt(x)>>hsqrt(500,10,20)")
3932 /// // plot sqrt(x) between 10 and 20 using 500 bins
3933 /// tree.Draw("sqrt(x):sin(y)>>hsqrt(100,10,60,50,.1,.5)")
3934 /// // plot sqrt(x) against sin(y)
3935 /// // 100 bins in x-direction; lower limit on x-axis is 10; upper limit is 60
3936 /// // 50 bins in y-direction; lower limit on y-axis is .1; upper limit is .5
3937 /// ~~~
3938 /// By default, the specified histogram is reset.
3939 /// To continue to append data to an existing histogram, use "+" in front
3940 /// of the histogram name.
3941 ///
3942 /// A '+' in front of the histogram name is ignored, when the name is followed by
3943 /// binning information as described in the previous paragraph.
3944 /// ~~~ {.cpp}
3945 /// tree.Draw("sqrt(x)>>+hsqrt","y>0")
3946 /// ~~~
3947 /// will not reset `hsqrt`, but will continue filling. This works for 1-D, 2-D
3948 /// and 3-D histograms.
3949 ///
3950 /// ### Accessing collection objects
3951 ///
3952 /// TTree::Draw default's handling of collections is to assume that any
3953 /// request on a collection pertain to it content. For example, if fTracks
3954 /// is a collection of Track objects, the following:
3955 /// ~~~ {.cpp}
3956 /// tree->Draw("event.fTracks.fPx");
3957 /// ~~~
3958 /// will plot the value of fPx for each Track objects inside the collection.
3959 /// Also
3960 /// ~~~ {.cpp}
3961 /// tree->Draw("event.fTracks.size()");
3962 /// ~~~
3963 /// would plot the result of the member function Track::size() for each
3964 /// Track object inside the collection.
3965 /// To access information about the collection itself, TTree::Draw support
3966 /// the '@' notation. If a variable which points to a collection is prefixed
3967 /// or postfixed with '@', the next part of the expression will pertain to
3968 /// the collection object. For example:
3969 /// ~~~ {.cpp}
3970 /// tree->Draw("event.@fTracks.size()");
3971 /// ~~~
3972 /// will plot the size of the collection referred to by `fTracks` (i.e the number
3973 /// of Track objects).
3974 ///
3975 /// ### Drawing 'objects'
3976 ///
3977 /// When a class has a member function named AsDouble or AsString, requesting
3978 /// to directly draw the object will imply a call to one of the 2 functions.
3979 /// If both AsDouble and AsString are present, AsDouble will be used.
3980 /// AsString can return either a char*, a std::string or a TString.s
3981 /// For example, the following
3982 /// ~~~ {.cpp}
3983 /// tree->Draw("event.myTTimeStamp");
3984 /// ~~~
3985 /// will draw the same histogram as
3986 /// ~~~ {.cpp}
3987 /// tree->Draw("event.myTTimeStamp.AsDouble()");
3988 /// ~~~
3989 /// In addition, when the object is a type TString or std::string, TTree::Draw
3990 /// will call respectively `TString::Data` and `std::string::c_str()`
3991 ///
3992 /// If the object is a TBits, the histogram will contain the index of the bit
3993 /// that are turned on.
3994 ///
3995 /// ### Retrieving information about the tree itself.
3996 ///
3997 /// You can refer to the tree (or chain) containing the data by using the
3998 /// string 'This'.
3999 /// You can then could any TTree methods. For example:
4000 /// ~~~ {.cpp}
4001 /// tree->Draw("This->GetReadEntry()");
4002 /// ~~~
4003 /// will display the local entry numbers be read.
4004 /// ~~~ {.cpp}
4005 /// tree->Draw("This->GetUserInfo()->At(0)->GetName()");
4006 /// ~~~
4007 /// will display the name of the first 'user info' object.
4008 ///
4009 /// ### Special functions and variables
4010 ///
4011 /// `Entry$`: A TTree::Draw formula can use the special variable `Entry$`
4012 /// to access the entry number being read. For example to draw every
4013 /// other entry use:
4014 /// ~~~ {.cpp}
4015 /// tree.Draw("myvar","Entry$%2==0");
4016 /// ~~~
4017 /// - `Entry$` : return the current entry number (`== TTree::GetReadEntry()`)
4018 /// - `LocalEntry$` : return the current entry number in the current tree of a
4019 /// chain (`== GetTree()->GetReadEntry()`)
4020 /// - `Entries$` : return the total number of entries (== TTree::GetEntries())
4021 /// - `LocalEntries$` : return the total number of entries in the current tree
4022 /// of a chain (== GetTree()->TTree::GetEntries())
4023 /// - `Length$` : return the total number of element of this formula for this
4024 /// entry (`==TTreeFormula::GetNdata()`)
4025 /// - `Iteration$` : return the current iteration over this formula for this
4026 /// entry (i.e. varies from 0 to `Length$`).
4027 /// - `Length$(formula )` : return the total number of element of the formula
4028 /// given as a parameter.
4029 /// - `Sum$(formula )` : return the sum of the value of the elements of the
4030 /// formula given as a parameter. For example the mean for all the elements in
4031 /// one entry can be calculated with: `Sum$(formula )/Length$(formula )`
4032 /// - `Min$(formula )` : return the minimun (within one TTree entry) of the value of the
4033 /// elements of the formula given as a parameter.
4034 /// - `Max$(formula )` : return the maximum (within one TTree entry) of the value of the
4035 /// elements of the formula given as a parameter.
4036 /// - `MinIf$(formula,condition)`
4037 /// - `MaxIf$(formula,condition)` : return the minimum (maximum) (within one TTree entry)
4038 /// of the value of the elements of the formula given as a parameter
4039 /// if they match the condition. If no element matches the condition,
4040 /// the result is zero. To avoid the resulting peak at zero, use the
4041 /// pattern:
4042 /// ~~~ {.cpp}
4043 /// tree->Draw("MinIf$(formula,condition)","condition");
4044 /// ~~~
4045 /// which will avoid calculation `MinIf$` for the entries that have no match
4046 /// for the condition.
4047 /// - `Alt$(primary,alternate)` : return the value of "primary" if it is available
4048 /// for the current iteration otherwise return the value of "alternate".
4049 /// For example, with arr1[3] and arr2[2]
4050 /// ~~~ {.cpp}
4051 /// tree->Draw("arr1+Alt$(arr2,0)");
4052 /// ~~~
4053 /// will draw arr1[0]+arr2[0] ; arr1[1]+arr2[1] and arr1[2]+0
4054 /// Or with a variable size array arr3
4055 /// ~~~ {.cpp}
4056 /// tree->Draw("Alt$(arr3[0],0)+Alt$(arr3[1],0)+Alt$(arr3[2],0)");
4057 /// ~~~
4058 /// will draw the sum arr3 for the index 0 to min(2,actual_size_of_arr3-1)
4059 /// As a comparison
4060 /// ~~~ {.cpp}
4061 /// tree->Draw("arr3[0]+arr3[1]+arr3[2]");
4062 /// ~~~
4063 /// will draw the sum arr3 for the index 0 to 2 only if the
4064 /// actual_size_of_arr3 is greater or equal to 3.
4065 /// Note that the array in 'primary' is flattened/linearized thus using
4066 /// `Alt$` with multi-dimensional arrays of different dimensions in unlikely
4067 /// to yield the expected results. To visualize a bit more what elements
4068 /// would be matched by TTree::Draw, TTree::Scan can be used:
4069 /// ~~~ {.cpp}
4070 /// tree->Scan("arr1:Alt$(arr2,0)");
4071 /// ~~~
4072 /// will print on one line the value of arr1 and (arr2,0) that will be
4073 /// matched by
4074 /// ~~~ {.cpp}
4075 /// tree->Draw("arr1-Alt$(arr2,0)");
4076 /// ~~~
4077 /// The ternary operator is not directly supported in TTree::Draw however, to plot the
4078 /// equivalent of `var2<20 ? -99 : var1`, you can use:
4079 /// ~~~ {.cpp}
4080 /// tree->Draw("(var2<20)*99+(var2>=20)*var1","");
4081 /// ~~~
4082 ///
4083 /// ### Drawing a user function accessing the TTree data directly
4084 ///
4085 /// If the formula contains a file name, TTree::MakeProxy will be used
4086 /// to load and execute this file. In particular it will draw the
4087 /// result of a function with the same name as the file. The function
4088 /// will be executed in a context where the name of the branches can
4089 /// be used as a C++ variable.
4090 ///
4091 /// For example draw px using the file hsimple.root (generated by the
4092 /// hsimple.C tutorial), we need a file named hsimple.cxx:
4093 /// ~~~ {.cpp}
4094 /// double hsimple() {
4095 /// return px;
4096 /// }
4097 /// ~~~
4098 /// MakeProxy can then be used indirectly via the TTree::Draw interface
4099 /// as follow:
4100 /// ~~~ {.cpp}
4101 /// new TFile("hsimple.root")
4102 /// ntuple->Draw("hsimple.cxx");
4103 /// ~~~
4104 /// A more complete example is available in the tutorials directory:
4105 /// `h1analysisProxy.cxx`, `h1analysProxy.h` and `h1analysisProxyCut.C`
4106 /// which reimplement the selector found in `h1analysis.C`
4107 ///
4108 /// The main features of this facility are:
4109 ///
4110 /// * on-demand loading of branches
4111 /// * ability to use the 'branchname' as if it was a data member
4112 /// * protection against array out-of-bound
4113 /// * ability to use the branch data as object (when the user code is available)
4114 ///
4115 /// See TTree::MakeProxy for more details.
4116 ///
4117 /// ### Making a Profile histogram
4118 ///
4119 /// In case of a 2-Dim expression, one can generate a TProfile histogram
4120 /// instead of a TH2F histogram by specifying option=prof or option=profs
4121 /// or option=profi or option=profg ; the trailing letter select the way
4122 /// the bin error are computed, See TProfile2D::SetErrorOption for
4123 /// details on the differences.
4124 /// The option=prof is automatically selected in case of y:x>>pf
4125 /// where pf is an existing TProfile histogram.
4126 ///
4127 /// ### Making a 2D Profile histogram
4128 ///
4129 /// In case of a 3-Dim expression, one can generate a TProfile2D histogram
4130 /// instead of a TH3F histogram by specifying option=prof or option=profs.
4131 /// or option=profi or option=profg ; the trailing letter select the way
4132 /// the bin error are computed, See TProfile2D::SetErrorOption for
4133 /// details on the differences.
4134 /// The option=prof is automatically selected in case of z:y:x>>pf
4135 /// where pf is an existing TProfile2D histogram.
4136 ///
4137 /// ### Making a 5D plot using GL
4138 ///
4139 /// If option GL5D is specified together with 5 variables, a 5D plot is drawn
4140 /// using OpenGL. See $ROOTSYS/tutorials/tree/staff.C as example.
4141 ///
4142 /// ### Making a parallel coordinates plot
4143 ///
4144 /// In case of a 2-Dim or more expression with the option=para, one can generate
4145 /// a parallel coordinates plot. With that option, the number of dimensions is
4146 /// arbitrary. Giving more than 4 variables without the option=para or
4147 /// option=candle or option=goff will produce an error.
4148 ///
4149 /// ### Making a candle sticks chart
4150 ///
4151 /// In case of a 2-Dim or more expression with the option=candle, one can generate
4152 /// a candle sticks chart. With that option, the number of dimensions is
4153 /// arbitrary. Giving more than 4 variables without the option=para or
4154 /// option=candle or option=goff will produce an error.
4155 ///
4156 /// ### Normalizing the output histogram to 1
4157 ///
4158 /// When option contains "norm" the output histogram is normalized to 1.
4159 ///
4160 /// ### Saving the result of Draw to a TEventList, a TEntryList or a TEntryListArray
4161 ///
4162 /// TTree::Draw can be used to fill a TEventList object (list of entry numbers)
4163 /// instead of histogramming one variable.
4164 /// If varexp0 has the form >>elist , a TEventList object named "elist"
4165 /// is created in the current directory. elist will contain the list
4166 /// of entry numbers satisfying the current selection.
4167 /// If option "entrylist" is used, a TEntryList object is created
4168 /// If the selection contains arrays, vectors or any container class and option
4169 /// "entrylistarray" is used, a TEntryListArray object is created
4170 /// containing also the subentries satisfying the selection, i.e. the indices of
4171 /// the branches which hold containers classes.
4172 /// Example:
4173 /// ~~~ {.cpp}
4174 /// tree.Draw(">>yplus","y>0")
4175 /// ~~~
4176 /// will create a TEventList object named "yplus" in the current directory.
4177 /// In an interactive session, one can type (after TTree::Draw)
4178 /// ~~~ {.cpp}
4179 /// yplus.Print("all")
4180 /// ~~~
4181 /// to print the list of entry numbers in the list.
4182 /// ~~~ {.cpp}
4183 /// tree.Draw(">>yplus", "y>0", "entrylist")
4184 /// ~~~
4185 /// will create a TEntryList object names "yplus" in the current directory
4186 /// ~~~ {.cpp}
4187 /// tree.Draw(">>yplus", "y>0", "entrylistarray")
4188 /// ~~~
4189 /// will create a TEntryListArray object names "yplus" in the current directory
4190 ///
4191 /// By default, the specified entry list is reset.
4192 /// To continue to append data to an existing list, use "+" in front
4193 /// of the list name;
4194 /// ~~~ {.cpp}
4195 /// tree.Draw(">>+yplus","y>0")
4196 /// ~~~
4197 /// will not reset yplus, but will enter the selected entries at the end
4198 /// of the existing list.
4199 ///
4200 /// ### Using a TEventList, TEntryList or TEntryListArray as Input
4201 ///
4202 /// Once a TEventList or a TEntryList object has been generated, it can be used as input
4203 /// for TTree::Draw. Use TTree::SetEventList or TTree::SetEntryList to set the
4204 /// current event list
4205 ///
4206 /// Example 1:
4207 /// ~~~ {.cpp}
4208 /// TEventList *elist = (TEventList*)gDirectory->Get("yplus");
4209 /// tree->SetEventList(elist);
4210 /// tree->Draw("py");
4211 /// ~~~
4212 /// Example 2:
4213 /// ~~~ {.cpp}
4214 /// TEntryList *elist = (TEntryList*)gDirectory->Get("yplus");
4215 /// tree->SetEntryList(elist);
4216 /// tree->Draw("py");
4217 /// ~~~
4218 /// If a TEventList object is used as input, a new TEntryList object is created
4219 /// inside the SetEventList function. In case of a TChain, all tree headers are loaded
4220 /// for this transformation. This new object is owned by the chain and is deleted
4221 /// with it, unless the user extracts it by calling GetEntryList() function.
4222 /// See also comments to SetEventList() function of TTree and TChain.
4223 ///
4224 /// If arrays are used in the selection criteria and TEntryListArray is not used,
4225 /// all the entries that have at least one element of the array that satisfy the selection
4226 /// are entered in the list.
4227 ///
4228 /// Example:
4229 /// ~~~ {.cpp}
4230 /// tree.Draw(">>pyplus","fTracks.fPy>0");
4231 /// tree->SetEventList(pyplus);
4232 /// tree->Draw("fTracks.fPy");
4233 /// ~~~
4234 /// will draw the fPy of ALL tracks in event with at least one track with
4235 /// a positive fPy.
4236 ///
4237 /// To select only the elements that did match the original selection
4238 /// use TEventList::SetReapplyCut or TEntryList::SetReapplyCut.
4239 ///
4240 /// Example:
4241 /// ~~~ {.cpp}
4242 /// tree.Draw(">>pyplus","fTracks.fPy>0");
4243 /// pyplus->SetReapplyCut(kTRUE);
4244 /// tree->SetEventList(pyplus);
4245 /// tree->Draw("fTracks.fPy");
4246 /// ~~~
4247 /// will draw the fPy of only the tracks that have a positive fPy.
4248 ///
4249 /// To draw only the elements that match a selection in case of arrays,
4250 /// you can also use TEntryListArray (faster in case of a more general selection).
4251 ///
4252 /// Example:
4253 /// ~~~ {.cpp}
4254 /// tree.Draw(">>pyplus","fTracks.fPy>0", "entrylistarray");
4255 /// tree->SetEntryList(pyplus);
4256 /// tree->Draw("fTracks.fPy");
4257 /// ~~~
4258 /// will draw the fPy of only the tracks that have a positive fPy,
4259 /// but without redoing the selection.
4260 ///
4261 /// Note: Use tree->SetEventList(0) if you do not want use the list as input.
4262 ///
4263 /// ### How to obtain more info from TTree::Draw
4264 ///
4265 /// Once TTree::Draw has been called, it is possible to access useful
4266 /// information still stored in the TTree object via the following functions:
4267 ///
4268 /// - GetSelectedRows() // return the number of values accepted by the selection expression. In case where no selection was specified, returns the number of values processed.
4269 /// - GetV1() // returns a pointer to the double array of V1
4270 /// - GetV2() // returns a pointer to the double array of V2
4271 /// - GetV3() // returns a pointer to the double array of V3
4272 /// - GetV4() // returns a pointer to the double array of V4
4273 /// - GetW() // returns a pointer to the double array of Weights where weight equal the result of the selection expression.
4274 ///
4275 /// where V1,V2,V3 correspond to the expressions in
4276 /// ~~~ {.cpp}
4277 /// TTree::Draw("V1:V2:V3:V4",selection);
4278 /// ~~~
4279 /// If the expression has more than 4 component use GetVal(index)
4280 ///
4281 /// Example:
4282 /// ~~~ {.cpp}
4283 /// Root > ntuple->Draw("py:px","pz>4");
4284 /// Root > TGraph *gr = new TGraph(ntuple->GetSelectedRows(),
4285 /// ntuple->GetV2(), ntuple->GetV1());
4286 /// Root > gr->Draw("ap"); //draw graph in current pad
4287 /// ~~~
4288 ///
4289 /// A more complete complete tutorial (treegetval.C) shows how to use the
4290 /// GetVal() method.
4291 ///
4292 /// creates a TGraph object with a number of points corresponding to the
4293 /// number of entries selected by the expression "pz>4", the x points of the graph
4294 /// being the px values of the Tree and the y points the py values.
4295 ///
4296 /// Important note: By default TTree::Draw creates the arrays obtained
4297 /// with GetW, GetV1, GetV2, GetV3, GetV4, GetVal with a length corresponding
4298 /// to the parameter fEstimate. The content will be the last `GetSelectedRows() % GetEstimate()`
4299 /// values calculated.
4300 /// By default fEstimate=1000000 and can be modified
4301 /// via TTree::SetEstimate. To keep in memory all the results (in case
4302 /// where there is only one result per entry), use
4303 /// ~~~ {.cpp}
4304 /// tree->SetEstimate(tree->GetEntries()+1); // same as tree->SetEstimate(-1);
4305 /// ~~~
4306 /// You must call SetEstimate if the expected number of selected rows
4307 /// you need to look at is greater than 1000000.
4308 ///
4309 /// You can use the option "goff" to turn off the graphics output
4310 /// of TTree::Draw in the above example.
4311 ///
4312 /// ### Automatic interface to TTree::Draw via the TTreeViewer
4313 ///
4314 /// A complete graphical interface to this function is implemented
4315 /// in the class TTreeViewer.
4316 /// To start the TTreeViewer, three possibilities:
4317 /// - select TTree context menu item "StartViewer"
4318 /// - type the command "TTreeViewer TV(treeName)"
4319 /// - execute statement "tree->StartViewer();"
4320 
4321 Long64_t TTree::Draw(const char* varexp, const char* selection, Option_t* option, Long64_t nentries, Long64_t firstentry)
4322 {
4323  GetPlayer();
4324  if (fPlayer)
4325  return fPlayer->DrawSelect(varexp,selection,option,nentries,firstentry);
4326  return -1;
4327 }
4328 
4329 ////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
4330 /// Remove some baskets from memory.
4331 
4332 void TTree::DropBaskets()
4333 {
4334  TBranch* branch = 0;
4335  Int_t nb = fBranches.GetEntriesFast();
4336  for (Int_t i = 0; i < nb; ++i) {
4337  branch = (TBranch*) fBranches.UncheckedAt(i);
4338  branch->DropBaskets("all");
4339  }
4340 }
4341 
4342 ////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
4343 /// Drop branch buffers to accommodate nbytes below MaxVirtualsize.
4344 
4345 void TTree::DropBuffers(Int_t)
4346 {
4347  // Be careful not to remove current read/write buffers.
4348  Int_t ndrop = 0;
4349  Int_t nleaves = fLeaves.GetEntriesFast();
4350  for (Int_t i = 0; i < nleaves; ++i) {
4351  TLeaf* leaf = (TLeaf*) fLeaves.UncheckedAt(i);
4352  TBranch* branch = (TBranch*) leaf->GetBranch();
4353  Int_t nbaskets = branch->GetListOfBaskets()->GetEntries();
4354  for (Int_t j = 0; j < nbaskets - 1; ++j) {
4355  if ((j == branch->GetReadBasket()) || (j == branch->GetWriteBasket())) {
4356  continue;
4357  }
4358  TBasket* basket = (TBasket*)branch->GetListOfBaskets()->UncheckedAt(j);
4359  if (basket) {
4360  ndrop += basket->DropBuffers();
4361  if (fTotalBuffers < fMaxVirtualSize) {
4362  return;
4363  }
4364  }
4365  }
4366  }
4367 }
4368 
4369 ////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
4370 /// Fill all branches.
4371 ///
4372 /// This function loops on all the branches of this tree. For
4373 /// each branch, it copies to the branch buffer (basket) the current
4374 /// values of the leaves data types. If a leaf is a simple data type,
4375 /// a simple conversion to a machine independent format has to be done.
4376 ///
4377 /// This machine independent version of the data is copied into a
4378 /// basket (each branch has its own basket). When a basket is full
4379 /// (32k worth of data by default), it is then optionally compressed
4380 /// and written to disk (this operation is also called committing or
4381 /// 'flushing' the basket). The committed baskets are then
4382 /// immediately removed from memory.
4383 ///
4384 /// The function returns the number of bytes committed to the
4385 /// individual branches.
4386 ///
4387 /// If a write error occurs, the number of bytes returned is -1.
4388 ///
4389 /// If no data are written, because, e.g., the branch is disabled,
4390 /// the number of bytes returned is 0.
4391 ///
4392 /// __The baskets are flushed and the Tree header saved at regular intervals__
4393 ///
4394 /// At regular intervals, when the amount of data written so far is
4395 /// greater than fAutoFlush (see SetAutoFlush) all the baskets are flushed to disk.
4396 /// This makes future reading faster as it guarantees that baskets belonging to nearby
4397 /// entries will be on the same disk region.
4398 /// When the first call to flush the baskets happen, we also take this opportunity
4399 /// to optimize the baskets buffers.
4400 /// We also check if the amount of data written is greater than fAutoSave (see SetAutoSave).
4401 /// In this case we also write the Tree header. This makes the Tree recoverable up to this point
4402 /// in case the program writing the Tree crashes.
4403 /// The decisions to FlushBaskets and Auto Save can be made based either on the number
4404 /// of bytes written (fAutoFlush and fAutoSave negative) or on the number of entries
4405 /// written (fAutoFlush and fAutoSave positive).
4406 /// Note that the user can decide to call FlushBaskets and AutoSave in her event loop
4407 /// base on the number of events written instead of the number of bytes written.
4408 ///
4409 /// Note that calling FlushBaskets too often increases the IO time.
4410 ///
4411 /// Note that calling AutoSave too often increases the IO time and also the file size.
4412 
4413 Int_t TTree::Fill()
4414 {
4415  Int_t nbytes = 0;
4416  Int_t nwrite = 0;
4417  Int_t nerror = 0;
4418  Int_t nbranches = fBranches.GetEntriesFast();
4419 
4420  // Case of one single super branch. Automatically update
4421  // all the branch addresses if a new object was created.
4422  if (nbranches == 1)
4423  ((TBranch *)fBranches.UncheckedAt(0))->UpdateAddress();
4424 
4425  if (fBranchRef)
4426  fBranchRef->Clear();
4427 
4428 #ifdef R__USE_IMT
4429  const auto useIMT = ROOT::IsImplicitMTEnabled() && fIMTEnabled;
4430  ROOT::Internal::TBranchIMTHelper imtHelper;
4431  if (useIMT) {
4432  fIMTFlush = true;
4433  fIMTZipBytes.store(0);
4434  fIMTTotBytes.store(0);
4435  }
4436 #endif
4437 
4438  for (Int_t i = 0; i < nbranches; ++i) {
4439  // Loop over all branches, filling and accumulating bytes written and error counts.
4440  TBranch *branch = (TBranch *)fBranches.UncheckedAt(i);
4441 
4442  if (branch->TestBit(kDoNotProcess))
4443  continue;
4444 
4445 #ifndef R__USE_IMT
4446  nwrite = branch->FillImpl(nullptr);
4447 #else
4448  nwrite = branch->FillImpl(useIMT ? &imtHelper : nullptr);
4449 #endif
4450  if (nwrite < 0) {
4451  if (nerror < 2) {
4452  Error("Fill", "Failed filling branch:%s.%s, nbytes=%d, entry=%lld\n"
4453  " This error is symptomatic of a Tree created as a memory-resident Tree\n"
4454  " Instead of doing:\n"
4455  " TTree *T = new TTree(...)\n"
4456  " TFile *f = new TFile(...)\n"
4457  " you should do:\n"
4458  " TFile *f = new TFile(...)\n"
4459  " TTree *T = new TTree(...)\n\n",
4460  GetName(), branch->GetName(), nwrite, fEntries + 1);
4461  } else {
4462  Error("Fill", "Failed filling branch:%s.%s, nbytes=%d, entry=%lld", GetName(), branch->GetName(), nwrite,
4463  fEntries + 1);
4464  }
4465  ++nerror;
4466  } else {
4467  nbytes += nwrite;
4468  }
4469  }
4470 
4471 #ifdef R__USE_IMT
4472  if (fIMTFlush) {
4473  imtHelper.Wait();
4474  fIMTFlush = false;
4475  const_cast<TTree *>(this)->AddTotBytes(fIMTTotBytes);
4476  const_cast<TTree *>(this)->AddZipBytes(fIMTZipBytes);
4477  nbytes += imtHelper.GetNbytes();
4478  nerror += imtHelper.GetNerrors();
4479  }
4480 #endif
4481 
4482  if (fBranchRef)
4483  fBranchRef->Fill();
4484 
4485  ++fEntries;
4486 
4487  if (fEntries > fMaxEntries)
4488  KeepCircular();
4489 
4490  if (gDebug > 0)
4491  Info("TTree::Fill", " - A: %d %lld %lld %lld %lld %lld %lld \n", nbytes, fEntries, fAutoFlush, fAutoSave,
4492  GetZipBytes(), fFlushedBytes, fSavedBytes);
4493 
4494  bool autoFlush = false;
4495  bool autoSave = false;
4496 
4497  if (fAutoFlush != 0 || fAutoSave != 0) {
4498  // Is it time to flush or autosave baskets?
4499  if (fFlushedBytes == 0) {
4500  // If fFlushedBytes == 0, it means we never flushed or saved, so
4501  // we need to check if it's time to do it and recompute the values
4502  // of fAutoFlush and fAutoSave in terms of the number of entries.
4503  // Decision can be based initially either on the number of bytes
4504  // or the number of entries written.
4505  Long64_t zipBytes = GetZipBytes();
4506 
4507  if (fAutoFlush)
4508  autoFlush = fAutoFlush < 0 ? (zipBytes > -fAutoFlush) : fEntries % fAutoFlush == 0;
4509 
4510  if (fAutoSave)
4511  autoSave = fAutoSave < 0 ? (zipBytes > -fAutoSave) : fEntries % fAutoSave == 0;
4512 
4513  if (autoFlush || autoSave) {
4514  // First call FlushBasket to make sure that fTotBytes is up to date.
4515  FlushBasketsImpl();
4516  autoFlush = false; // avoid auto flushing again later
4517 
4518  // When we are in one-basket-per-cluster mode, there is no need to optimize basket:
4519  // they will automatically grow to the size needed for an event cluster (with the basket
4520  // shrinking preventing them from growing too much larger than the actually-used space).
4521  if (!TestBit(TTree::kOnlyFlushAtCluster)) {
4522  OptimizeBaskets(GetTotBytes(), 1, "");
4523  if (gDebug > 0)
4524  Info("TTree::Fill", "OptimizeBaskets called at entry %lld, fZipBytes=%lld, fFlushedBytes=%lld\n",
4525  fEntries, GetZipBytes(), fFlushedBytes);
4526  }
4527  fFlushedBytes = GetZipBytes();
4528  fAutoFlush = fEntries; // Use test on entries rather than bytes
4529 
4530  // subsequently in run
4531  if (fAutoSave < 0) {
4532  // Set fAutoSave to the largest integer multiple of
4533  // fAutoFlush events such that fAutoSave*fFlushedBytes
4534  // < (minus the input value of fAutoSave)
4535  Long64_t totBytes = GetTotBytes();
4536  if (zipBytes != 0) {
4537  fAutoSave = TMath::Max(fAutoFlush, fEntries * ((-fAutoSave / zipBytes) / fEntries));
4538  } else if (totBytes != 0) {
4539  fAutoSave = TMath::Max(fAutoFlush, fEntries * ((-fAutoSave / totBytes) / fEntries));
4540  } else {
4541  TBufferFile b(TBuffer::kWrite, 10000);
4542  TTree::Class()->WriteBuffer(b, (TTree *)this);
4543  Long64_t total = b.Length();
4544  fAutoSave = TMath::Max(fAutoFlush, fEntries * ((-fAutoSave / total) / fEntries));
4545  }
4546  } else if (fAutoSave > 0) {
4547  fAutoSave = fAutoFlush * (fAutoSave / fAutoFlush);
4548  }
4549 
4550  if (fAutoSave != 0 && fEntries >= fAutoSave)
4551  autoSave = true;
4552 
4553  if (gDebug > 0)
4554  Info("TTree::Fill", "First AutoFlush. fAutoFlush = %lld, fAutoSave = %lld\n", fAutoFlush, fAutoSave);
4555  }
4556  } else {
4557  // Check if we need to auto flush
4558  if (fAutoFlush) {
4559  if (fNClusterRange == 0)
4560  autoFlush = fEntries > 1 && fEntries % fAutoFlush == 0;
4561  else
4562  autoFlush = (fEntries - (fClusterRangeEnd[fNClusterRange - 1] + 1)) % fAutoFlush == 0;
4563  }
4564  // Check if we need to auto save
4565  if (fAutoSave)
4566  autoSave = fEntries % fAutoSave == 0;
4567  }
4568  }
4569 
4570  if (autoFlush) {
4571  FlushBasketsImpl();
4572  if (gDebug > 0)
4573  Info("TTree::Fill", "FlushBaskets() called at entry %lld, fZipBytes=%lld, fFlushedBytes=%lld\n", fEntries,
4574  GetZipBytes(), fFlushedBytes);
4575  fFlushedBytes = GetZipBytes();
4576  }
4577 
4578  if (autoSave) {
4579  AutoSave(); // does not call FlushBasketsImpl() again
4580  if (gDebug > 0)
4581  Info("TTree::Fill", "AutoSave called at entry %lld, fZipBytes=%lld, fSavedBytes=%lld\n", fEntries,
4582  GetZipBytes(), fSavedBytes);
4583  }
4584 
4585  // Check that output file is still below the maximum size.
4586  // If above, close the current file and continue on a new file.
4587  // Currently, the automatic change of file is restricted
4588  // to the case where the tree is in the top level directory.
4589  if (fDirectory)
4590  if (TFile *file = fDirectory->GetFile())
4591  if ((TDirectory *)file == fDirectory && (file->GetEND() > fgMaxTreeSize))
4592  ChangeFile(file);
4593 
4594  return nerror == 0 ? nbytes : -1;
4595 }
4596 
4597 ////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
4598 /// Search in the array for a branch matching the branch name,
4599 /// with the branch possibly expressed as a 'full' path name (with dots).
4600 
4601 static TBranch *R__FindBranchHelper(TObjArray *list, const char *branchname) {
4602  if (list==0 || branchname == 0 || branchname[0] == '\0') return 0;
4603 
4604  Int_t nbranches = list->GetEntries();
4605 
4606  UInt_t brlen = strlen(branchname);
4607 
4608  for(Int_t index = 0; index < nbranches; ++index) {
4609  TBranch *where = (TBranch*)list->UncheckedAt(index);
4610 
4611  const char *name = where->GetName();
4612  UInt_t len = strlen(name);
4613  if (len && name[len-1]==']') {
4614  const char *dim = strchr(name,'[');
4615  if (dim) {
4616  len = dim - name;
4617  }
4618  }
4619  if (brlen == len && strncmp(branchname,name,len)==0) {
4620  return where;
4621  }
4622  TBranch *next = 0;
4623  if ((brlen >= len) && (branchname[len] == '.')
4624  && strncmp(name, branchname, len) == 0) {
4625  // The prefix subbranch name match the branch name.
4626 
4627  next = where->FindBranch(branchname);
4628  if (!next) {
4629  next = where->FindBranch(branchname+len+1);
4630  }
4631  if (next) return next;
4632  }
4633  const char *dot = strchr((char*)branchname,'.');
4634  if (dot) {
4635  if (len==(size_t)(dot-branchname) &&
4636  strncmp(branchname,name,dot-branchname)==0 ) {
4637  return R__FindBranchHelper(where->GetListOfBranches(),dot+1);
4638  }
4639  }
4640  }
4641  return 0;
4642 }
4643 
4644 ////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
4645 /// Return the branch that correspond to the path 'branchname', which can
4646 /// include the name of the tree or the omitted name of the parent branches.
4647 /// In case of ambiguity, returns the first match.
4648 
4649 TBranch* TTree::FindBranch(const char* branchname)
4650 {
4651  // We already have been visited while recursively looking
4652  // through the friends tree, let return
4653  if (kFindBranch & fFriendLockStatus) {
4654  return 0;
4655  }
4656 
4657  TBranch* branch = 0;
4658  // If the first part of the name match the TTree name, look for the right part in the
4659  // list of branches.
4660  // This will allow the branchname to be preceded by
4661  // the name of this tree.
4662  if (strncmp(fName.Data(),branchname,fName.Length())==0 && branchname[fName.Length()]=='.') {
4663  branch = R__FindBranchHelper( GetListOfBranches(), branchname + fName.Length() + 1);
4664  if (branch) return branch;
4665  }
4666  // If we did not find it, let's try to find the full name in the list of branches.
4667  branch = R__FindBranchHelper(GetListOfBranches(), branchname);
4668  if (branch) return branch;
4669 
4670  // If we still did not find, let's try to find it within each branch assuming it does not the branch name.
4671  TIter next(GetListOfBranches());
4672  while ((branch = (TBranch*) next())) {
4673  TBranch* nestedbranch = branch->FindBranch(branchname);
4674  if (nestedbranch) {
4675  return nestedbranch;
4676  }
4677  }
4678 
4679  // Search in list of friends.
4680  if (!fFriends) {
4681  return 0;
4682  }
4683  TFriendLock lock(this, kFindBranch);
4684  TIter nextf(fFriends);
4685  TFriendElement* fe = 0;
4686  while ((fe = (TFriendElement*) nextf())) {
4687  TTree* t = fe->GetTree();
4688  if (!t) {
4689  continue;
4690  }
4691  // If the alias is present replace it with the real name.
4692  const char *subbranch = strstr(branchname, fe->GetName());
4693  if (subbranch != branchname) {
4694  subbranch = 0;
4695  }
4696  if (subbranch) {
4697  subbranch += strlen(fe->GetName());
4698  if (*subbranch != '.') {
4699  subbranch = 0;
4700  } else {
4701  ++subbranch;
4702  }
4703  }
4704  std::ostringstream name;
4705  if (subbranch) {
4706  name << t->GetName() << "." << subbranch;
4707  } else {
4708  name << branchname;
4709  }
4710  branch = t->FindBranch(name.str().c_str());
4711  if (branch) {
4712  return branch;
4713  }
4714  }
4715  return 0;
4716 }
4717 
4718 ////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
4719 /// Find leaf..
4720 
4721 TLeaf* TTree::FindLeaf(const char* searchname)
4722 {
4723  // We already have been visited while recursively looking
4724  // through the friends tree, let's return.
4725  if (kFindLeaf & fFriendLockStatus) {
4726  return 0;
4727  }
4728 
4729  // This will allow the branchname to be preceded by
4730  // the name of this tree.
4731  char* subsearchname = (char*) strstr(searchname, GetName());
4732  if (subsearchname != searchname) {
4733  subsearchname = 0;
4734  }
4735  if (subsearchname) {
4736  subsearchname += strlen(GetName());
4737  if (*subsearchname != '.') {
4738  subsearchname = 0;
4739  } else {
4740  ++subsearchname;
4741  if (subsearchname[0]==0) {
4742  subsearchname = 0;
4743  }
4744  }
4745  }
4746 
4747  TString leafname;
4748  TString leaftitle;
4749  TString longname;
4750  TString longtitle;
4751 
4752  const bool searchnameHasDot = strchr(searchname, '.') != nullptr;
4753 
4754  // For leaves we allow for one level up to be prefixed to the name.
4755  TIter next(GetListOfLeaves());
4756  TLeaf* leaf = 0;
4757  while ((leaf = (TLeaf*) next())) {
4758  leafname = leaf->GetName();
4759  Ssiz_t dim = leafname.First('[');
4760  if (dim >= 0) leafname.Remove(dim);
4761 
4762  if (leafname == searchname) {
4763  return leaf;
4764  }
4765  if (subsearchname && leafname == subsearchname) {
4766  return leaf;
4767  }
4768  // The TLeafElement contains the branch name
4769  // in its name, let's use the title.
4770  leaftitle = leaf->GetTitle();
4771  dim = leaftitle.First('[');
4772  if (dim >= 0) leaftitle.Remove(dim);
4773 
4774  if (leaftitle == searchname) {
4775  return leaf;
4776  }
4777  if (subsearchname && leaftitle == subsearchname) {
4778  return leaf;
4779  }
4780  if (!searchnameHasDot)
4781  continue;
4782  TBranch* branch = leaf->GetBranch();
4783  if (branch) {
4784  longname.Form("%s.%s",branch->GetName(),leafname.Data());
4785  dim = longname.First('[');
4786  if (dim>=0) longname.Remove(dim);
4787  if (longname == searchname) {
4788  return leaf;
4789  }
4790  if (subsearchname && longname == subsearchname) {
4791  return leaf;
4792  }
4793  longtitle.Form("%s.%s",branch->GetName(),leaftitle.Data());
4794  dim = longtitle.First('[');
4795  if (dim>=0) longtitle.Remove(dim);
4796  if (longtitle == searchname) {
4797  return leaf;
4798  }
4799  if (subsearchname && longtitle == subsearchname) {
4800  return leaf;
4801  }
4802  // The following is for the case where the branch is only
4803  // a sub-branch. Since we do not see it through
4804  // TTree::GetListOfBranches, we need to see it indirectly.
4805  // This is the less sturdy part of this search ... it may
4806  // need refining ...
4807  if (strstr(searchname, ".") && !strcmp(searchname, branch->GetName())) {
4808  return leaf;
4809  }
4810  if (subsearchname && strstr(subsearchname, ".") && !strcmp(subsearchname, branch->GetName())) {
4811  return leaf;
4812  }
4813  }
4814  }
4815  // Search in list of friends.
4816  if (!fFriends) {
4817  return 0;
4818  }
4819  TFriendLock lock(this, kFindLeaf);
4820  TIter nextf(fFriends);
4821  TFriendElement* fe = 0;
4822  while ((fe = (TFriendElement*) nextf())) {
4823  TTree* t = fe->GetTree();
4824  if (!t) {
4825  continue;
4826  }
4827  // If the alias is present replace it with the real name.
4828  subsearchname = (char*) strstr(searchname, fe->GetName());
4829  if (subsearchname != searchname) {
4830  subsearchname = 0;
4831  }
4832  if (subsearchname) {
4833  subsearchname += strlen(fe->GetName());
4834  if (*subsearchname != '.') {
4835  subsearchname = 0;
4836  } else {
4837  ++subsearchname;
4838  }
4839  }
4840  if (subsearchname) {
4841  leafname.Form("%s.%s",t->GetName(),subsearchname);
4842  } else {
4843  leafname = searchname;
4844  }
4845  leaf = t->FindLeaf(leafname);
4846  if (leaf) {
4847  return leaf;
4848  }
4849  }
4850  return 0;
4851 }

4853 ////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
4854 /// Fit a projected item(s) from a tree.
4855 ///
4856 /// funcname is a TF1 function.
4857 ///
4858 /// See TTree::Draw() for explanations of the other parameters.
4859 ///
4860 /// By default the temporary histogram created is called htemp.
4861 /// If varexp contains >>hnew , the new histogram created is called hnew
4862 /// and it is kept in the current directory.
4863 ///
4864 /// The function returns the number of selected entries.
4865 ///
4866 /// Example:
4867 /// ~~~ {.cpp}

4869 /// ~~~
4870 /// will fit sqrt(x) and save the histogram as "hsqrt" in the current
4871 /// directory.
4872 ///

4879 /// (i.e. fitResult is null if the fit is OK)
4880 
4881 Int_t TTree::Fit(const char* funcname, const char* varexp, const char* selection, Option_t* option, Option_t* goption, Long64_t nentries, Long64_t firstentry)
4882 {
4883  GetPlayer();
4884  if (fPlayer) {
4885  return fPlayer->Fit(funcname, varexp, selection, option, goption, nentries, firstentry);
4886  }
4887  return -1;
4888 }

4890 namespace {
4891 struct BoolRAIIToggle {
4892  Bool_t &m_val;
4893 
4894  BoolRAIIToggle(Bool_t &val) : m_val(val) { m_val = true; }
4895  ~BoolRAIIToggle() { m_val = false; }

4898 
4899 ////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
4900 /// Write to disk all the basket that have not yet been individually written and
4901 /// create an event cluster boundary (by default).
4902 ///
4903 /// If the caller wishes to flush the baskets but not create an event cluster,
4904 /// then set create_cluster to false.
4905 ///
4906 /// If ROOT has IMT-mode enabled, this will launch multiple TBB tasks in parallel
4907 /// via TThreadExecutor to do this operation; one per basket compression. If the
4908 /// caller utilizes TBB also, care must be taken to prevent deadlocks.
4909 ///
4910 /// For example, let's say the caller holds mutex A and calls FlushBaskets; while
4911 /// TBB is waiting for the ROOT compression tasks to complete, it may decide to
4912 /// run another one of the user's tasks in this thread. If the second user task
4913 /// tries to acquire A, then a deadlock will occur. The example call sequence
4914 /// looks like this:
4915 ///
4916 /// - User acquires mutex A
4917 /// - User calls FlushBaskets.
4918 /// - ROOT launches N tasks and calls wait.
4919 /// - TBB schedules another user task, T2.
4920 /// - T2 tries to acquire mutex A.
4921 ///
4922 /// At this point, the thread will deadlock: the code may function with IMT-mode
4923 /// disabled if the user assumed the legacy code never would run their own TBB
4924 /// tasks.
4925 ///
4926 /// SO: users of TBB who want to enable IMT-mode should carefully review their
4927 /// locking patterns and make sure they hold no coarse-grained application
4928 /// locks when they invoke ROOT.
4929 ///
4930 /// Return the number of bytes written or -1 in case of write error.
4931 Int_t TTree::FlushBaskets(Bool_t create_cluster) const
4932 {
4933  Int_t retval = FlushBasketsImpl();
4934  if (retval == -1) return retval;
4935 
4936  if (create_cluster) const_cast<TTree *>(this)->MarkEventCluster();
4937  return retval;
4938 }
4939 
4940 ////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
4941 /// Internal implementation of the FlushBaskets algorithm.
4942 /// Unlike the public interface, this does NOT create an explicit event cluster
4943 /// boundary; it is up to the (internal) caller to determine whether that should
4944 /// done.
4945 ///
4946 /// Otherwise, the comments for FlushBaskets applies.
4947 ///
4948 Int_t TTree::FlushBasketsImpl() const
4949 {
4950  if (!fDirectory) return 0;
4951  Int_t nbytes = 0;
4952  Int_t nerror = 0;
4953  TObjArray *lb = const_cast<TTree*>(this)->GetListOfBranches();
4954  Int_t nb = lb->GetEntriesFast();
4955 
4956 #ifdef R__USE_IMT
4957  const auto useIMT = ROOT::IsImplicitMTEnabled() && fIMTEnabled;
4958  if (useIMT) {
4959  // ROOT-9668: here we need to check if the size of fSortedBranches is different from the
4960  // size of the list of branches before triggering the initialisation of the fSortedBranches
4961  // container to cover two cases:
4962  // 1. This is the first time we flush. fSortedBranches is empty and we need to fill it.
4963  // 2. We flushed at least once already but a branch has been be added to the tree since then
4964  if (fSortedBranches.size() != unsigned(nb)) { const_cast<TTree*>(this)->InitializeBranchLists(false); }
4965 
4966  BoolRAIIToggle sentry(fIMTFlush);
4967  fIMTZipBytes.store(0);
4968  fIMTTotBytes.store(0);
4969  std::atomic<Int_t> nerrpar(0);
4970  std::atomic<Int_t> nbpar(0);
4971  std::atomic<Int_t> pos(0);
4972 
4973  auto mapFunction = [&]() {
4974  // The branch to process is obtained when the task starts to run.
4975  // This way, since branches are sorted, we make sure that branches
4976  // leading to big tasks are processed first. If we assigned the
4977  // branch at task creation time, the scheduler would not necessarily
4978  // respect our sorting.
4979  Int_t j = pos.fetch_add(1);
4980 
4981  auto branch = fSortedBranches[j].second;
4982  if (R__unlikely(!branch)) { return; }
4983 
4984  if (R__unlikely(gDebug > 0)) {
4985  std::stringstream ss;
4986  ss << std::this_thread::get_id();
4987  Info("FlushBaskets", "[IMT] Thread %s", ss.str().c_str());
4988  Info("FlushBaskets", "[IMT] Running task for branch #%d: %s", j, branch->GetName());
4989  }
4990 
4991  Int_t nbtask = branch->FlushBaskets();
4992 
4993  if (nbtask < 0) { nerrpar++; }
4994  else { nbpar += nbtask; }
4995  };
4996 
4997  ROOT::TThreadExecutor pool;
4998  pool.Foreach(mapFunction, nb);
4999 
5000  fIMTFlush = false;
5001  const_cast<TTree*>(this)->AddTotBytes(fIMTTotBytes);
5002  const_cast<TTree*>(this)->AddZipBytes(fIMTZipBytes);
5003 
5004  return nerrpar ? -1 : nbpar.load();
5005  }
5006 #endif
5007  for (Int_t j = 0; j < nb; j++) {
5008  TBranch* branch = (TBranch*) lb->UncheckedAt(j);
5009  if (branch) {
5010  Int_t nwrite = branch->FlushBaskets();
5011  if (nwrite<0) {
5012  ++nerror;
5013  } else {
5014  nbytes += nwrite;
5015  }
5016  }
5017  }
5018  if (nerror) {
5019  return -1;
5020  } else {
5021  return nbytes;
5022  }
5023 }
5024 
5025 ////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
5026 /// Returns the expanded value of the alias. Search in the friends if any.
5027 
5028 const char* TTree::GetAlias(const char* aliasName) const
5029 {
5030  // We already have been visited while recursively looking
5031  // through the friends tree, let's return.
5032  if (kGetAlias & fFriendLockStatus) {
5033  return 0;
5034  }
5035  if (fAliases) {
5036  TObject* alias = fAliases->FindObject(aliasName);
5037  if (alias) {
5038  return alias->GetTitle();
5039  }
5040  }
5041  if (!fFriends) {
5042  return 0;
5043  }
5044  TFriendLock lock(const_cast<TTree*>(this), kGetAlias);
5045  TIter nextf(fFriends);
5046  TFriendElement* fe = 0;
5047  while ((fe = (TFriendElement*) nextf())) {
5048  TTree* t = fe->GetTree();
5049  if (t) {
5050  const char* alias = t->GetAlias(aliasName);
5051  if (alias) {
5052  return alias;
5053  }
5054  const char* subAliasName = strstr(aliasName, fe->GetName());
5055  if (subAliasName && (subAliasName[strlen(fe->GetName())] == '.')) {
5056  alias = t->GetAlias(aliasName + strlen(fe->GetName()) + 1);
5057  if (alias) {
5058  return alias;
5059  }
5060  }
5061  }
5062  }
5063  return 0;
5064 }
5065 
5066 ////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
5067 /// Return pointer to the branch with the given name in this tree or its friends.
5068 
5069 TBranch* TTree::GetBranch(const char* name)
5070 {
5071  if (name == 0) return 0;
5072 
5073  // We already have been visited while recursively
5074  // looking through the friends tree, let's return.
5075  if (kGetBranch & fFriendLockStatus) {
5076  return 0;
5077  }
5078 
5079  // Search using branches.
5080  Int_t nb = fBranches.GetEntriesFast();
5081  for (Int_t i = 0; i < nb; i++) {
5082  TBranch* branch = (TBranch*) fBranches.UncheckedAt(i);
5083  if (!branch) {
5084  continue;
5085  }
5086  if (!strcmp(branch->GetName(), name)) {
5087  return branch;
5088  }
5089  TObjArray* lb = branch->GetListOfBranches();
5090  Int_t nb1 = lb->GetEntriesFast();
5091  for (Int_t j = 0; j < nb1; j++) {
5092  TBranch* b1 = (TBranch*) lb->UncheckedAt(j);
5093  if (!strcmp(b1->GetName(), name)) {
5094  return b1;
5095  }
5096  TObjArray* lb1 = b1->GetListOfBranches();
5097  Int_t nb2 = lb1->GetEntriesFast();
5098  for (Int_t k = 0; k < nb2; k++) {
5099  TBranch* b2 = (TBranch*) lb1->UncheckedAt(k);
5100  if (!strcmp(b2->GetName(), name)) {
5101  return b2;
5102  }
5103  }
5104  }
5105  }
5106 
5107  // Search using leaves.
5108  TObjArray* leaves = GetListOfLeaves();
5109  Int_t nleaves = leaves->GetEntriesFast();
5110  for (Int_t i = 0; i < nleaves; i++) {
5111  TLeaf* leaf = (TLeaf*) leaves->UncheckedAt(i);
5112  TBranch* branch = leaf->GetBranch();
5113  if (!strcmp(branch->GetName(), name)) {
5114  return branch;
5115  }
5116  }
5117 
5118  if (!fFriends) {
5119  return 0;
5120  }
5121 
5122  // Search in list of friends.
5123  TFriendLock lock(this, kGetBranch);
5124  TIter next(fFriends);
5125  TFriendElement* fe = 0;
5126  while ((fe = (TFriendElement*) next())) {
5127  TTree* t = fe->GetTree();
5128  if (t) {
5129  TBranch* branch = t->GetBranch(name);
5130  if (branch) {
5131  return branch;
5132  }
5133  }
5134  }
5135 
5136  // Second pass in the list of friends when
5137  // the branch name is prefixed by the tree name.
5138  next.Reset();
5139  while ((fe = (TFriendElement*) next())) {
5140  TTree* t = fe->GetTree();
5141  if (!t) {
5142  continue;
5143  }
5144  char* subname = (char*) strstr(name, fe->GetName());
5145  if (subname != name) {
5146  continue;
5147  }
5148  Int_t l = strlen(fe->GetName());
5149  subname += l;
5150  if (*subname != '.') {
5151  continue;
5152  }
5153  subname++;
5154  TBranch* branch = t->GetBranch(subname);
5155  if (branch) {
5156  return branch;
5157  }
5158  }
5159  return 0;
5160 }

5188 ////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
5189 /// Used for automatic sizing of the cache.
5190 ///
5191 /// Estimates a suitable size for the tree cache based on AutoFlush.
5192 /// A cache sizing factor is taken from the configuration. If this yields zero
5193 /// and withDefault is true the historical algorithm for default size is used.
5194 
5195 Long64_t TTree::GetCacheAutoSize(Bool_t withDefault /* = kFALSE */ ) const
5196 {
5197  const char *stcs;
5198  Double_t cacheFactor = 0.0;
5199  if (!(stcs = gSystem->Getenv("ROOT_TTREECACHE_SIZE")) || !*stcs) {
5200  cacheFactor = gEnv->GetValue("TTreeCache.Size", 1.0);
5201  } else {
5202  cacheFactor = TString(stcs).Atof();
5203  }
5204 
5205  if (cacheFactor < 0.0) {
5206  // ignore negative factors
5207  cacheFactor = 0.0;
5208  }
5209 
5210  Long64_t cacheSize = 0;
5211 
5212  if (fAutoFlush < 0) cacheSize = Long64_t(-cacheFactor*fAutoFlush);
5213  else if (fAutoFlush == 0) cacheSize = 0;
5214  else cacheSize = Long64_t(cacheFactor*1.5*fAutoFlush*GetZipBytes()/(fEntries+1));
5215 
5216  if (cacheSize >= (INT_MAX / 4)) {
5217  cacheSize = INT_MAX / 4;
5218  }
5219 
5220  if (cacheSize < 0) {
5221  cacheSize = 0;
5222  }
5223 
5224  if (cacheSize == 0 && withDefault) {
5225  if (fAutoFlush < 0) cacheSize = -fAutoFlush;
5226  else if (fAutoFlush == 0) cacheSize = 0;
5227  else cacheSize = Long64_t(1.5*fAutoFlush*GetZipBytes()/(fEntries+1));
5228  }
5229 
5230  return cacheSize;
5231 }

5300 
5301 ////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
5302 /// Read all branches of entry and return total number of bytes read.
5303 ///
5304 /// - `getall = 0` : get only active branches
5305 /// - `getall = 1` : get all branches
5306 ///
5307 /// The function returns the number of bytes read from the input buffer.
5308 /// If entry does not exist the function returns 0.
5309 /// If an I/O error occurs, the function returns -1.
5310 ///
5311 /// If the Tree has friends, also read the friends entry.
5312 ///
5313 /// To activate/deactivate one or more branches, use TBranch::SetBranchStatus
5314 /// For example, if you have a Tree with several hundred branches, and you
5315 /// are interested only by branches named "a" and "b", do
5316 /// ~~~ {.cpp}
5317 /// mytree.SetBranchStatus("*",0); //disable all branches
5318 /// mytree.SetBranchStatus("a",1);
5319 /// mytree.SetBranchStatus("b",1);
5320 /// ~~~
5321 /// when calling mytree.GetEntry(i); only branches "a" and "b" will be read.
5322 ///
5323 /// __WARNING!!__
5324 /// If your Tree has been created in split mode with a parent branch "parent.",
5325 /// ~~~ {.cpp}
5326 /// mytree.SetBranchStatus("parent",1);
5327 /// ~~~
5328 /// will not activate the sub-branches of "parent". You should do:
5329 /// ~~~ {.cpp}
5330 /// mytree.SetBranchStatus("parent*",1);
5331 /// ~~~
5332 /// Without the trailing dot in the branch creation you have no choice but to
5333 /// call SetBranchStatus explicitly for each of the sub branches.
5334 ///
5335 /// An alternative is to call directly
5336 /// ~~~ {.cpp}
5337 /// brancha.GetEntry(i)
5338 /// branchb.GetEntry(i);
5339 /// ~~~
5340 /// ## IMPORTANT NOTE
5341 ///
5342 /// By default, GetEntry reuses the space allocated by the previous object
5343 /// for each branch. You can force the previous object to be automatically
5344 /// deleted if you call mybranch.SetAutoDelete(kTRUE) (default is kFALSE).
5345 ///
5346 /// Example:
5347 ///
5348 /// Consider the example in $ROOTSYS/test/Event.h
5349 /// The top level branch in the tree T is declared with:
5350 /// ~~~ {.cpp}
5351 /// Event *event = 0; //event must be null or point to a valid object
5352 /// //it must be initialized
5353 /// T.SetBranchAddress("event",&event);
5354 /// ~~~
5355 /// When reading the Tree, one can choose one of these 3 options:
5356 ///
5357 /// ## OPTION 1
5358 ///
5359 /// ~~~ {.cpp}
5360 /// for (Long64_t i=0;i<nentries;i++) {
5361 /// T.GetEntry(i);
5362 /// // the object event has been filled at this point
5363 /// }
5364 /// ~~~
5365 /// The default (recommended). At the first entry an object of the class
5366 /// Event will be created and pointed by event. At the following entries,
5367 /// event will be overwritten by the new data. All internal members that are
5368 /// TObject* are automatically deleted. It is important that these members
5369 /// be in a valid state when GetEntry is called. Pointers must be correctly
5370 /// initialized. However these internal members will not be deleted if the
5371 /// characters "->" are specified as the first characters in the comment
5372 /// field of the data member declaration.
5373 ///
5374 /// If "->" is specified, the pointer member is read via pointer->Streamer(buf).
5375 /// In this case, it is assumed that the pointer is never null (case of
5376 /// pointer TClonesArray *fTracks in the Event example). If "->" is not
5377 /// specified, the pointer member is read via buf >> pointer. In this case
5378 /// the pointer may be null. Note that the option with "->" is faster to
5379 /// read or write and it also consumes less space in the file.
5380 ///
5381 /// ## OPTION 2
5382 ///
5383 /// The option AutoDelete is set
5384 /// ~~~ {.cpp}
5385 /// TBranch *branch = T.GetBranch("event");
5386 /// branch->SetAddress(&event);
5387 /// branch->SetAutoDelete(kTRUE);
5388 /// for (Long64_t i=0;i<nentries;i++) {
5389 /// T.GetEntry(i);
5390 /// // the object event has been filled at this point
5391 /// }
5392 /// ~~~
5393 /// In this case, at each iteration, the object event is deleted by GetEntry
5394 /// and a new instance of Event is created and filled.
5395 ///
5396 /// ## OPTION 3
5397 ///
5398 /// ~~~ {.cpp}
5399 /// Same as option 1, but you delete yourself the event.
5400 ///
5401 /// for (Long64_t i=0;i<nentries;i++) {
5402 /// delete event;
5403 /// event = 0; // EXTREMELY IMPORTANT
5404 /// T.GetEntry(i);
5405 /// // the object event has been filled at this point
5406 /// }
5407 /// ~~~
5408 /// It is strongly recommended to use the default option 1. It has the
5409 /// additional advantage that functions like TTree::Draw (internally calling
5410 /// TTree::GetEntry) will be functional even when the classes in the file are
5411 /// not available.
5412 ///
5413 /// Note: See the comments in TBranchElement::SetAddress() for the
5414 /// object ownership policy of the underlying (user) data.
5415 
5416 Int_t TTree::GetEntry(Long64_t entry, Int_t getall)
5417 {
5418 
5419  // We already have been visited while recursively looking
5420  // through the friends tree, let return
5421  if (kGetEntry & fFriendLockStatus) return 0;
5422 
5423  if (entry < 0 || entry >= fEntries) return 0;
5424  Int_t i;
5425  Int_t nbytes = 0;
5426  fReadEntry = entry;
5427 
5428  // create cache if wanted
5429  if (fCacheDoAutoInit)
5430  SetCacheSizeAux();
5431 
5432  Int_t nbranches = fBranches.GetEntriesUnsafe();
5433  Int_t nb=0;
5434 
5435  auto seqprocessing = [&]() {
5436  TBranch *branch;
5437  for (i=0;i<nbranches;i++) {
5438  branch = (TBranch*)fBranches.UncheckedAt(i);
5439  nb = branch->GetEntry(entry, getall);
5440  if (nb < 0) break;
5441  nbytes += nb;
5442  }
5443  };
5444 
5445 #ifdef R__USE_IMT
5446  if (nbranches > 1 && ROOT::IsImplicitMTEnabled() && fIMTEnabled && !TTreeCacheUnzip::IsParallelUnzip()) {
5447  if (fSortedBranches.empty())
5448  InitializeBranchLists(true);
5449 
5450  // Count branches are processed first and sequentially
5451  for (auto branch : fSeqBranches) {
5452  nb = branch->GetEntry(entry, getall);
5453  if (nb < 0) break;
5454  nbytes += nb;
5455  }
5456  if (nb < 0) return nb;
5457 
5458  // Enable this IMT use case (activate its locks)
5459  ROOT::Internal::TParBranchProcessingRAII pbpRAII;
5460 
5461  Int_t errnb = 0;
5462  std::atomic<Int_t> pos(0);
5463  std::atomic<Int_t> nbpar(0);
5464 
5465  auto mapFunction = [&]() {
5466  // The branch to process is obtained when the task starts to run.
5467  // This way, since branches are sorted, we make sure that branches
5468  // leading to big tasks are processed first. If we assigned the
5469  // branch at task creation time, the scheduler would not necessarily
5470  // respect our sorting.
5471  Int_t j = pos.fetch_add(1);
5472 
5473  Int_t nbtask = 0;
5474  auto branch = fSortedBranches[j].second;
5475 
5476  if (gDebug > 0) {
5477  std::stringstream ss;
5478  ss << std::this_thread::get_id();
5479  Info("GetEntry", "[IMT] Thread %s", ss.str().c_str());
5480  Info("GetEntry", "[IMT] Running task for branch #%d: %s", j, branch->GetName());
5481  }
5482 
5483  std::chrono::time_point<std::chrono::system_clock> start, end;
5484 
5485  start = std::chrono::system_clock::now();
5486  nbtask = branch->GetEntry(entry, getall);
5487  end = std::chrono::system_clock::now();
5488 
5489  Long64_t tasktime = (Long64_t)std::chrono::duration_cast<std::chrono::microseconds>(end - start).count();
5490  fSortedBranches[j].first += tasktime;
5491 
5492  if (nbtask < 0) errnb = nbtask;
5493  else nbpar += nbtask;
5494  };
5495 
5496  ROOT::TThreadExecutor pool;
5497  pool.Foreach(mapFunction, fSortedBranches.size());
5498 
5499  if (errnb < 0) {
5500  nb = errnb;
5501  }
5502  else {
5503  // Save the number of bytes read by the tasks
5504  nbytes += nbpar;
5505 
5506  // Re-sort branches if necessary
5507  if (++fNEntriesSinceSorting == kNEntriesResort) {
5508  SortBranchesByTime();
5509  fNEntriesSinceSorting = 0;
5510  }
5511  }
5512  }
5513  else {
5514  seqprocessing();
5515  }
5516 #else
5517  seqprocessing();
5518 #endif
5519  if (nb < 0) return nb;
5520 
5521  // GetEntry in list of friends
5522  if (!fFriends) return nbytes;
5523  TFriendLock lock(this,kGetEntry);
5524  TIter nextf(fFriends);
5525  TFriendElement *fe;
5526  while ((fe = (TFriendElement*)nextf())) {
5527  TTree *t = fe->GetTree();
5528  if (t) {
5529  if (fe->TestBit(TFriendElement::kFromChain)) {
5530  nb = t->GetEntry(t->GetReadEntry(),getall);
5531  } else {
5532  if ( t->LoadTreeFriend(entry,this) >= 0 ) {
5533  nb = t->GetEntry(t->GetReadEntry(),getall);
5534  } else nb = 0;
5535  }
5536  if (nb < 0) return nb;
5537  nbytes += nb;
5538  }
5539  }
5540  return nbytes;
5541 }
5542 
5543 
5544 ////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
5545 /// Divides the top-level branches into two vectors: (i) branches to be
5546 /// processed sequentially and (ii) branches to be processed in parallel.
5547 /// Even if IMT is on, some branches might need to be processed first and in a
5548 /// sequential fashion: in the parallelization of GetEntry, those are the
5549 /// branches that store the size of another branch for every entry
5550 /// (e.g. the size of an array branch). If such branches were processed
5551 /// in parallel with the rest, there could be two threads invoking
5552 /// TBranch::GetEntry on one of them at the same time, since a branch that
5553 /// depends on a size (or count) branch will also invoke GetEntry on the latter.
5554 /// This method can be invoked several times during the event loop if the TTree
5555 /// is being written, for example when adding new branches. In these cases, the
5556 /// `checkLeafCount` parameter is false.
5557 /// \param[in] checkLeafCount True if we need to check whether some branches are
5558 /// count leaves.
5559 
5560 void TTree::InitializeBranchLists(bool checkLeafCount)
5561 {
5562  Int_t nbranches = fBranches.GetEntriesFast();
5563 
5564  // The special branch fBranchRef needs to be processed sequentially:
5565  // we add it once only.
5566  if (fBranchRef && fBranchRef != fSeqBranches[0]) {
5567  fSeqBranches.push_back(fBranchRef);
5568  }
5569 
5570  // The branches to be processed sequentially are those that are the leaf count of another branch
5571  if (checkLeafCount) {
5572  for (Int_t i = 0; i < nbranches; i++) {
5573  TBranch* branch = (TBranch*)fBranches.UncheckedAt(i);
5574  auto leafCount = ((TLeaf*)branch->GetListOfLeaves()->At(0))->GetLeafCount();
5575  if (leafCount) {
5576  auto countBranch = leafCount->GetBranch();
5577  if (std::find(fSeqBranches.begin(), fSeqBranches.end(), countBranch) == fSeqBranches.end()) {
5578  fSeqBranches.push_back(countBranch);
5579  }
5580  }
5581  }
5582  }
5583 
5584  // Any branch that is not a leaf count can be safely processed in parallel when reading
5585  // We need to reset the vector to make sure we do not re-add several times the same branch.
5586  if (!checkLeafCount) {
5587  fSortedBranches.clear();
5588  }
5589  for (Int_t i = 0; i < nbranches; i++) {
5590  Long64_t bbytes = 0;
5591  TBranch* branch = (TBranch*)fBranches.UncheckedAt(i);
5592  if (std::find(fSeqBranches.begin(), fSeqBranches.end(), branch) == fSeqBranches.end()) {
5593  bbytes = branch->GetTotBytes("*");
5594  fSortedBranches.emplace_back(bbytes, branch);
5595  }
5596  }
5597 
5598  // Initially sort parallel branches by size
5599  std::sort(fSortedBranches.begin(),
5600  fSortedBranches.end(),
5601  [](std::pair<Long64_t,TBranch*> a, std::pair<Long64_t,TBranch*> b) {
5602  return a.first > b.first;
5603  });
5604 
5605  for (size_t i = 0; i < fSortedBranches.size(); i++) {
5606  fSortedBranches[i].first = 0LL;
5607  }
5608 }
5609 
5610 ////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
5611 /// Sorts top-level branches by the last average task time recorded per branch.
5612 
5613 void TTree::SortBranchesByTime()
5614 {
5615  for (size_t i = 0; i < fSortedBranches.size(); i++) {
5616  fSortedBranches[i].first *= kNEntriesResortInv;
5617  }
5618 
5619  std::sort(fSortedBranches.begin(),
5620  fSortedBranches.end(),
5621  [](std::pair<Long64_t,TBranch*> a, std::pair<Long64_t,TBranch*> b) {
5622  return a.first > b.first;
5623  });
5624 
5625  for (size_t i = 0; i < fSortedBranches.size(); i++) {
5626  fSortedBranches[i].first = 0LL;
5627  }
5628 }
